Situation A. Using a Number Line

Mr. Bernoski’s class wrote to the Montana weather station to see how math was used in tracking and predicting the weather. The director of the station put together some situations for the class to analyze using a number line.

Suppose the temperature rose from –4°F to 45°F as shown on the number line.
n represents the temperature change. Since it is an arrow moving in the positive direction, it represents adding 49°F.
–4 + n = 45 represents the temperature of -4°F changing by n degrees with the new temperature is 45°F. Since the difference between 45 and -4 is 49, then n = 49°F.
4. Suppose the temperature dropped from 45°F to –4°F. How would you represent this on the number line? An equation?
5. How is the sign of the change in temperature reflected on the number line? Equation?

In the number line, n still represents the temperature change. But now the temperature is dropping, so the arrow goes to the negative direction, it represents adding negative 49°F.

In the equation, 45 + n = –4 represents the temperature of 45°F changing by n degrees with the new temperature is -4°F. Since the difference between -4 and 45 is -49, then n = -49°F.

Situation B. Matching Representations for Temperature Change

The temperature change for six days is represented on a number line and with an equation.

Match the number line and equation that represents the change in each Day. What is the change?

  • Sunday: 20°F to –10°F
  • Monday: –20°F to –10°F
  • Tuesday: –20°F to 10°F
  • Wednesday: –10°F to –20°F
  • Thursday: 20°F to 10°F
  • Friday: 10°F to 20°F

• Sunday → Number Line B → Eq. 3, n = -30
  • Monday → Number Line E → Eq. 6, n = 10
  • Tuesday → Number Line D → Eq. 2, n = 30
  • Wednesday → Number Line F → Eq. 4, n = -10
  • Thursday → Number Line A → Eq. 1, n = -10
  • Friday → Number Line C → Eq. 5, n = 10

Note: It is important for students to remember that n represents the change from one number to another. It represents both the distance and the increase or decrease of the number.

For example, with Equation 1 and Number Line A, n “tells us” that the original value will change by a decrease of 10 (we represent this with a -10). When we add the original value with the change, we find the resulting value.

Situation C. Rising and Falling

For each change in the temperature, begin with the same starting temperature. Find the missing information. Explain your thinking.
